constitutes a life that is not materialistic? It seems to me that the very notion of materialism carries a negative connotation, but in the same breath, we have failed to define what a non-materialistic society consists of.

\nI then move to my next question: what about materialism is negative? We've explored one possible option, in the sense that spending and consuming goods that are perhaps overpriced or have unclear amounts of utility may be wrong (depsite proving that there is some utility, perhaps even more utility, in having people create and distribute these expensive goods). Perhaps another route is that the very structure of having to consume is a net negative. \n

explored two possible arguments as to why materialism may be wrong; the first consisting of spending lavishly doesn't bring any utility to society, and the second exploring the very proposition of materialism being a negative.
